<head3>(Record Lines Off Top\record_lines)

<p>

Lines that are scrolled off the top of the DECterm display are 
saved by default.  To view these lines, use the
vertical scroll bar.  
If you do not want to save lines that 
are scrolled from the display, click on the Record Lines Off Top option.
                 
<head3>(Vertical Scroll Bar\vertical_sb)

<p>
DECterm displays vertical scroll bars by default.  If you do not want
vertical scroll bars, click on the Vertical Scroll Bar option.

<head3>(Horizontal Scroll Bar\horizontal_sb)

<p>
DECterm does not display a horizontal scroll bar by default.
  Click on
Horizontal Scroll Bar to display a horizontal scroll bar at the
bottom of your DECterm window.

<head3>(Vertical Cursor Coupling\vertical_cc)

<p>

When you change the window or
the size of DECterm vertically, the cursor remains visible by default.
  For example, if the display
contains 24 rows and you shrink it to 5 rows, the cursor remains visible and
allows you to enter text.  Click on 
the Vertical Cursor Coupling option to disable this option.
             
<head3>(Horizontal Cursor Coupling\horizontal_cc)

<p>
When you change the size of the window or DECterm horizontally  
(for example, from 132 columns to 80 columns) the cursor is 
not
visible by default.  You can change the display by clicking on the Horizontal
Cursor Coupling option. 

<head3>(Auto Wrap\auto_wrap)


<p>
When the cursor reaches the right margin it 
does not move to the next line by default.  
Each character typed deletes 
the last character. Click on Auto Wrap to allow
the cursor to automatically start a new line.


<head3>(Display Cursor\display_cursor)

<p>
DECterm displays a cursor by default.
Click on the Display Cursor option for the cursor to become invisible.


<head3>(Cursor Blink\cursor_blink)

<p>

The DECterm cursor blinks by default.

Click on the Cursor Blink option to display 
a non-blinking cursor.



<head3>(Batch Scroll Lines\batch_scroll)

<p>

DECterm updates the display on a character or line
basis by default.  Batch scrolling allows updates on a specified number
of lines.  Enter the number of lines in the text entry box to establish
a batch.
  


<head3>(Record Lines Off Top\transcript_size)

<p>


DECterm saves 500 lines in the transcript by default.
To increase or decrease the number of lines saved in the 
transcript, enter a number from 1 to 9999 in the 
text entry box.


Recording lines requires a corresponding
amount of virtual memory.  Modification of quotas or
SYSGEN parameters may be required.
   

<head3>(Dark Text, Light Background\dark_text)

<p>
DECterm displays dark text on a light
screen background by default.  

Click on the Light Text, Dark Background option
to reverse the display to light text on a dark screen background.

<head3>(Light Text, Dark Background\light_text)

<p>
DECterm displays dark text on a light screen background by default.

Click on the Light Text, Dark Background option
to reverse the display to light text on a dark screen background.



<head3>(No Status Display\no_status)

<p>

DECterm does not receive host status
messages by default.  
Host status messages, when activated, appear on the bottom line of
the DECterm display.


<head3>(Host Status Display\host_status)

<p>

To receive host status messages, click on the Host Status Display
option.  This 
causes messages to appear on the bottom line of the DECterm window.
You can set Host Status Display only on VT300-series terminals.



<head3>(Block Cursor\block_cursor)

<p>

The cursor displayed in your DECterm
window is shaped like a block by default.
You can change the shape of the cursor by clicking on the
Underline Cursor option.

<head3>(Underline Cursor\underline)

<p>
The default cursor for DECterm is a block.
Click on the
Underline Cursor option to get an underline cursor.


