<head3>(Newline\newline)

<p>
When DECterm receives a line feed (LF), form feed (FF), or
vertical tab (VT) character, the cursor moves to the first column
of the next line.  When you press Return, both a 
carriage return (CR) and line feed are received.
<p>
If you click on the Newline option and DECterm receives an LF,
FF, or VT character, the cursor movers to the current column of the 
next line.  When you press Return, DECterm only sends a CR.

<head3>(Lock UDKs\lock_udks)

<p>

Your keyboard contains User Defined Keys (UDKs).
The host system can change the
function of the key you have defined 
 back to the default.  Clicking on Lock UDKs 
ensures that the host system cannot change your definitions.
<p>

<head3>(Lock User Features\lock_features)

<p>

DECterm lets you change the Auto Repeat option and the Foreground and
Background Display option.  The host system cannot override
these options if you click on the Lock User Features option.

<head3>(Local Echo\local_echo)

<p>

When the "Local Echo" button is selected, DECterm will display all typed
input on the screen.

<p>
The display of these characters is independent of any character echoing
that may take place on the host to which the DECterm is connected.  Use
of this feature will usually cause typed text to be displayed twice.


<head3>(Normal Cursor Keys\normal_cursor)

<p>                 

By default, the Normal Cursor Keys option is on.  This 
causes the
arrow keys to move the cursor up, down, left, and right.

<head3>(Appl Cursor Keys\appl_cursor)

<p>

By clicking on the Appl Cursor Keys option, you can override the
Normal Cursor Keys default and set the arrow keys to application-specific
functions.




